    {
      "source": "evaluator",
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm editing a biology paper and i keep seeing a lot of passive voice. can u explain how to spot it and how i should actually fix it so the sentences are more direct?"
    },
    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The passive voice can be a sneaky thing, but spotting it is relatively easy. You'll often see it when the subject of the sentence is replaced by a form of the verb, like \"the experiment was conducted\" instead of \"the researcher conducted the experiment.\" To identify passive voice, look for verbs that are preceded by \"was,\" \"were,\" or \"been.\" \n\nNow, let's talk about fixing it. One way to rewrite passive voice sentences is to make the subject the focus of the sentence. For example, \"The experiment was conducted by the researcher\" becomes \"The researcher conducted the experiment.\" This is called active voice, and it's usually more direct and clear. \n\nAnother way to fix passive voice is to use a phrase like \"by [name]\" or \"with [name]\" to indicate who or what is performing the action. For instance, \"The report was written by the team\" becomes \"The team wrote the report.\" This can add clarity and help the reader understand who's responsible for the action.",
